   {:e #blake3 "2036f2abac1e3d2895954f6060a872895c60d08d52fc3e3bc7e4b2a136d64353" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :session/s-1774480855; Session entity: :task/t-196aed9a\nThe cascade package (internal/cascade/) performs impact analysis: given a changed spec element ID, it traces through module_relationships to find all affected modules and domains. Despite having a Depth option (1-5), the current implementation only does single-hop analysis — the depth parameter is assigned but unused (line 48: _ = depth // reserved for future multi-hop cascade). This means cascade analysis underestimates transitive impact. The package is tiny (158 lines + 34-line renderer) and delegates all data access to storage.GetModuleRelationships, GetBacklinks, etc. It classifies affected modules as owner/consumer/peer based on relationship type.; The witness package (internal/witness/) implements a multi-level evidence hierarchy for invariant verification (APP-ADR-030). Level 1: attestation (human claims it works). Level 2: test evidence (test name/file). Level 3: mechanical verification (--verify flag scans code annotations matching ddis:implements/maintains pattern and cross-references with validation_method). Level 4: review bundle (--review-context outputs Gestalt-Theory-framed context including code snippets, review criteria, and violation scenarios). Witnesses carry code_hash and auto-invalidate when code changes (APP-INV-041). This creates a provenance chain: spec element -> witness record -> code annotation -> test file.; Extreme fan-in coupling: the storage package is imported by 77 other files across the codebase — more than twice the next most-imported package (events at 29). This makes storage the critical bottleneck for the entire system. The storage package concentrates all SQL in two monolithic files: queries.go (43KB) and insert.go (30KB) with no interface abstraction — every consumer takes *sql.DB directly. There are no repository interfaces, no dependency injection points, making the storage layer untestable in isolation and creating a tight coupling between every feature and SQLite. This is a classic god-package anti-pattern where the data layer becomes the implicit API contract.; The drift package (internal/drift/) implements triple-axis drift measurement: implementation drift (unspecified, unimplemented, contradictions), intent drift (uncovered non-negotiables, purposeless elements), and process drift (spec-first ratio, tool intermediation, witness coverage, validate gating). Drift classification has 3 dimensions: direction (impl-ahead, spec-ahead, contradictory, mutual), severity (additive, contradictory, structural), and intentionality (planned, accidental, organic). Quality breakdown decomposes drift into correctness/depth/coherence to guide remediation priority. The remediate.go file suggests automated remediation generation. Two SPIKE files (37KB total) indicate active design exploration around comparison targets and intent semantics.; The parser package (internal/parser/) handles both monolith and modular spec formats via manifest.yaml (APP-ADR-010). It parses DDIS-specific constructs: invariants (invariants.go with regex-based block extraction), ADRs (adrs.go), negative specs (negspecs.go), gates, glossary, verification blocks, performance requirements, and whynot blocks. The statemachine.go uses a state machine pattern for section-level parsing. The manifest.yaml declares modules with explicit dependency edges (maintains, interfaces, implements, adjacent) — forming a dependency DAG that the rest of the CLI uses for ordering and validation.; The storage package (internal/storage/) implements a 30-table normalized SQLite schema (APP-ADR-005). Tables include spec_index, source_files, sections, invariants, adrs, negspecs, gates, verification, glossary, examples, cross_references, performance_reqs, and snapshots. Every table uses content_hash TEXT NOT NULL for integrity verification. The schema uses extensive CHECK constraints and foreign keys, suggesting strong data integrity guarantees. The package is split into db.go (connection), schema.go (DDL), models.go (Go structs), queries.go (43KB of SQL), insert.go (30KB of inserts), and storage_test.go (22KB).; Cross-cutting architectural pattern: the codebase uses structured code annotations (ddis:implements, ddis:maintains) totaling 296 occurrences across 86 Go files. These annotations serve as the primary traceability mechanism between specification (97 invariants, 74 ADRs) and implementation. The annotations are machine-parseable by the annotate package (grammar.go defines the grammar, scan.go walks the code tree). The witness package uses these annotations for Level 3 mechanical verification. However, the annotation density is uneven: cli/ files average 2-3 annotations each while some domain packages (cascade, skeleton, impact) have only 1. The discover vs discovery package duplication (both exist) suggests naming confusion in the package structure.; The consistency package implements a 5-tier contradiction detection engine: Tier 2 (graph — typed edges, governance overlap, cycles), Tier 3 (SAT — gophersat CDCL solver encoding semi-formal expressions as CNF), Tier 4 (heuristic — polarity/quantifier/numeric rules + LSI semantic), Tier 5 (SMT — Z3 subprocess with SMT-LIB2 for QF_LIA/QF_UF/LIA), Tier 6 (LLM-as-judge via Anthropic API). Tiers run sequentially, results deduplicated by element pair keeping highest confidence. Z3 and LLM tiers gracefully degrade when unavailable. The ConflictType enum has 9 variants covering structural, logical, and semantic tensions. The package totals ~90KB across 11 files.; Critical testing gap: of 38 internal packages, 15 have ZERO test files: bundle, cascade, diff, exemplar, impact, implorder, oplog, progress, query, renderer, skeleton, state. The packages WITH tests average only 1.3 test files per package. The cli package (54 .go files, the largest by far) has only 1 test file (cli_test.go). The storage package (43KB queries.go + 30KB insert.go) has only 1 test file. Meanwhile, the consistency package has the best test:source ratio at 3:8. Test coverage is concentrated in core logic (consistency, materialize, witness) while integration code (cli, storage queries) is barely tested.; The events package (internal/events/) implements a three-stream event-sourcing architecture (APP-ADR-015). Stream 1 is discovery (ideas, questions, decisions), Stream 2 is specification (parse, validate, drift), Stream 3 is implementation (issues, status, findings). Each stream writes to a separate JSONL file. Events use SHA-256 content hashing for deduplication (APP-INV-020) and carry causal predecessor chains (APP-INV-074). Events have a Version field for forward compatibility (APP-INV-072). The payloads.go file defines typed payloads for each event type including ParsePayload, DriftPayload, WitnessPayload, and ChallengePayload." :op :assert}
